<br>
Fearing things into obstacles, duplication tricks, getting mobs stuck on geometry, and using safe spots are pretty clear cut examples of exploits.  I know of a way to kill certain types of mobs with certain types of characters in complete safety, it is certainly an exploit, but even then I wound up using it a few times before I was aware of what was going on. Once I realized the bug I went out of my way to avoid those situations though.<br>
<br>
While getting the high level group buffs at low levels probably is an exploit, many of the people taking advantage of it might not realize that they are exploiting a bug. There are other spells that require grouping without having a level limit, invisibility  comes to mind, and it is true of group effect bard songs as well. <br>
<br>
It is even possible, though less likely, that the people casting the spell don't realize it can't be cast with lower level people targetted. They may just habitually target themselves when casting group spells (I do that). I was surprised the first time I tried to cast Boon of the Garou on someone who was under 44. I got the message that they 'were not worthy' of the spell, not even clearly that they were not high enough level. In fact, since I was level 44 and it was in a group I was fighting with, I didn't expect that to be a problem.<br>
<br>
The real clue should be how overpowering the spell is at those levels. I think that fixing it might be more difficult than some people here seem to think, and that might be part of the reason it hasn't been changed yet. In the short term, they probably could cut the duration of KEI in half, which might make it less desirable (though the people who want it would come back twice as often.) It would be interesting if they could code group buffs to scale in effectiveness acording to the recipient's level, so that KEI is no better than clarity at level 20. That probably would be difficult though.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nicolheartsbane>Nicol Heartsbane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist</span><br>  Posts: 932<br> <font color=#ffffff>(3/31/03 1:44:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25564.topic&index=65>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.hiwaay.net/~kostrom/erudite.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re</span><hr size=1> I have posted on many occasions that I consider high level buffs on low level players to be a bad and imbalancing implementation.  The blame for this can ONLY be placed on sony, as this is clearly NOT an exploit.  You cast KEI, person in group gets KEI, the spell works as intended.<br>
<br>
I don't think you were even playing, Whiz, when group spells checked against everyone in the group before refusing to cast.  This implementation was a major pain in the ass, and the level limits for the spells were often not reasonable or fair.  Additionally, you could not cast a self-only buff if you had a low level character targeted, also a major pain in the ass.<br>
<br>
Verant changed it so that you could cast the group spells instead of asking level-appropriate people to disband while you cast a buff.  The way it works now is an intentional change away from a bad implementation that has been proposed in this thread a few times.<br>
<br>
Go forward a few years and now much more powerful group buffs with extremely long duration are available, and land on low level group members for extremely imbalancing effects.  You see that people are upset about imbalance, and rightly so.  Will calling this an exploit be a useful rhetorical tool in convincing sony to do something?  If so, go ahead.<br>
<br>
My own opinion is that all buffs should land on all players, but should have reduced effectiveness if there is a sufficient level difference.  Buffs should have recommended levels.  KEI should simply generate a lot less mana on a low level character.  On the other hand, I should be able to cast levitation on a player who can freaking cast levitate on herself anyway, but doesn't have bat wings.<br>
