<br>
There are two types of bugs: data bugs, and coding bugs.<br>
<br>
A data bug is when someone enters the wrong data into the game design, this includes things like pathing maps, item stats, spell effects, etc.<br>
<br>
A coding bug is a mistake or oversight in the way code is written.  Including things like carrying so much copper that your weight becomes negative, the ability to stack certain spells that aren't supposed to be stacked, etc.<br>
<br>
Things that are commonly called exploits, but aren't (although they might be against the rules):<br>
<br>
1. Spawn camping is not exploiting a bug, because there is no bug involved. (example of a rule that has nothing to do with any kind of bug)<br>
<br>
2. Gravity Fluxing yourself to heights / Pulling with Eye of Zomm.  (example of relative coding, effects that can be negative or positive, depending on the situation, you can't have it both ways)<br>
<br>
3. Mob warping / Nuking through walls / Summoning through locked doors. (examples of poor design and bad solutions to particular problems, rather than fixing the bug itself, programmers add extra code that &quot;compensates&quot; for a bug, kind of like fixing a leaky pipe by heating the water so it evaporates before it hits the ground)<br>
<br>
4. Manastone + cheal / negative spells not stacking with rez effects / corpse dragging. (examples of lack of foresight, designers fail to realize all possible uses and applications)<br>
<br>
There are more examples, but the word exploit is so misused it isn't funny..<br>
<br>
Merloc<br>
