<br>
In the attempt to come up with a &quot;logical definition&quot; of an exploit, these features are proposed as a means to identify an explit:<br>
1) intentional action<br>
2) resulting in unfair advantage or reward<br>
3) by means of something unintended, or a &quot;bug&quot;<br>
<br>
This position is best stated in Goladus's post:<br>
An exploit is a situation that exists such that a player can take advantage of a bug or unintended design consequence to achieve an unfair advantage over other players, especially in terms of items, platinum, experience, or spawn competition. Also any situation that allows harassment of other players or the ability to make gains with zero risk would be an exploit. More generally, the use of bugs and unintended features to generally break the foundations of the game and make it generally less fun.<br>
<br>
In order to analyze this definition, I propose that we look at the logical requirements of a definition, and then start testing the definition to see if it identifies exploits and non-exploits correctly.  <br>
<br>
A definition should provide necessary and sufficient conditions.  In other words, it must tell you what is and what is not an exploit.  In evaluating the definition, we will have to examine several cases, and see how it stacks up against what we expect, and what Verant has ruled.  I have prepared a list of cases, mostly from this thread.  Many of these I consider to be obviously exploits, or obviously not exploits, but if we are looking at a definition, we have to be sure it agrees on obvious cases.<br>
<br>
a) Killing mobs from safe spots.<br>
b) Using corpse dragging to simulate CoH where disabled.<br>
c) Using tradeskill containers to transfer nodrop items.<br>
d) Using summon corpse to hop islands in sky.<br>
e) Casting KEI on low level players.<br>
f) Charming a very powerful mob to kill a named with great loot solo, when a full group or more would be needed for a conventional fight.<br>
g) Splitting pulls by means of feign death.<br>
h) Quad kiting.<br>
i) Using high level equipment on a low level character.<br>
j) Powerleveling using non-damage abilities to help.<br>
k) Powerleveling with memory blur.<br>
l) Pulling the Dain to the pits under icewell keep.<br>
m) Using fear where a mob runs away to one spot and stays there.<br>
<br>
