<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Q. I think someone on my server is exploiting a quest.  He has pulled the two NPCs close together so he can get the quest item and turn it in very quickly. Is this ok for him to do or should I report him?<br>
<br>
A. This is indeed an exploit.  Please report this with a petition as soon as you notice.  Be sure to include the name of the player involved, the name of the NPCs, the zone that player was in, and what the person was doing at the time.<br>
<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Now, this seems to refer directly to this quest: <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://everquest.allakhazam.com/db/quest.html?quest=141">everquest.allakhazam.com/db/quest.html?quest=141</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Problem is that this is a pretty old quest.  Erudin's been around for awhile, and I challenge you guys to find a site that lists this quest and doesn't specifically mention hauling Slansin up to Toresian.  Most people that have used this quest have at least considered doing this.  It's also easy to do, since nothing in the Tower of Erudin assists Slansin if you pull him and root him up there.  There is also some risk involved depending on your level, since Slansin's lvl 10, if you tried this at the first level you got root, he'd probably drop you before you managed to get up the stairs.  While I might understand the issue if this was on a different quest, my question is, 'Who does this hurt?'<br>
<br>
The only major advantage you get out of this exploit is that you don't have to run up and down 3 flights of stairs anymore.  Anyone else trying the quest isn't hurt by having the NPCs this close, since they still can complete the quest.  The exp gain is also pretty marginal.  Unless you've got a major running fetish, I don't see the harm.  Yes, Slansin has been moved out of his location, but he's only there for one quest, and he's now right next to the NPC that starts the quest.  Is there some kind of problem with people getting lost five feet from where they started?<br>
<br>
If SOE wanted to fix this one, they'd have had ample time to do so, all they'd really need to do is make Toresian assist Slansin.  Changing one NPC would have the effect of rendering this quest exploit a deathtrap, as everything else in that room would auto assist Toresian, and that many lvl 60 casters would burn you down pretty fast.  I have personally used this exploit before, though I've since started doing it the long way after reading the FAQ.<br>
<br>
That may have been a bad example, but I think it illustrates a major point I have on what is and is not an exploit, HARM.  If you can prove to me that something is damaging to other players, then I can see the point about banning it.  <br>
<br>
I've schooled a lot of tanks who think quadding is an exploit by letting them watch what happens when I actually do it.  All it usually takes is one good snare resist, or getting stunned by moving just a little too close to my mobs for them to see the actual risk we take soloing this way.  When they see the work I actually have to put into first planning it out and then doing it, they generally change their opinions of the tactic.  <br>
<br>
One of the major problems with any kind of list like this one is that even this late into the game, we still have no clear concise definition of what we should and should not be able to do.  Look at the class descriptions for example, they give only the most bare boned information on what each class is capable of.  We started out 'masters of DD', then 'masters of arcane teleportation'.  I expect to be 'master of Cabilis's sewage system' by sometime next year.  They're inconsistent over time, and they don't really give you much info beyond the RP aspect and a very general overview.  If someone came out and wrote up: &quot;a wizard's job in a group is to do X, to assist in doing Y, and to pull off Z when all else fails&quot;, that would probably help with some of the problems we see in the game now.  Also, how is a group supposed to work according to: &quot;The Vision&quot;?  I've never seen &quot;The Vision&quot;, and I'm of the opinion that keeping this secret from us, even long after they've supposedly dumped it in favor of &quot;fun&quot;, is a mistake.  <br>
<br>
If I can't see how I'm supposed to be playing, how do I know if I'm doing anything wrong?<br>
<br>
That line probably seems stupid, but think about it for a second.  If someone had done all the up-front work on writing out exactly how they expected the game to work, and what each class's role was, would we have as many problems today defining what exploits are, and have to continually ban or warn players about them?  Yes, that style is more than a little limiting, and penalizes players for 'thinking outside the box', but is it really realistic to send people into a world with a pat on the back and a few toys to play with, then punish them for using those toys later because they don't conform to our unwritten rules?  While I don't personally advocate using any form of exploit, the enforcement policy does seem overly arbitrary at this point.  If you're going to punish me, at least spell out for me what is and is not legal before the feds start knocking down my door.<br>
<br>
Zerlatik Flaimweaver<br>
Sorcerer of Tholuxe Paells<br>
